    <string name="first_onboard_guide_title">Aura-Mesh guide</string>

    <string name="first_onboard_01_title">Aura-Mesh</string>
    <string name="first_onboard_01_body">Aura-Mesh connects your phone to a compatible LoRa mesh network over Bluetooth, USB, or TCP where the build supports it. You get channel and direct messaging, node lists, a map with live positions and temporary beacons, full radio and device configuration, optional offline maps, and background-friendly delivery so conversations keep working while you use the phone.</string>
    <string name="first_onboard_02_title">Your node identity</string>
    <string name="first_onboard_02_body">Bind the app to your hardware with a node ID and password and keep a saved session so you can reopen the mesh quickly after each cold start without repeating the whole setup every time.</string>
    <string name="first_onboard_03_title">How you connect</string>
    <string name="first_onboard_03_body">Pick the transport that fits your setup—Bluetooth, local IP, or a wired serial bridge—and let the app finish negotiation and synchronization so data and settings can flow reliably to the radio.</string>
    <string name="first_onboard_04_title">Mesh channels</string>
    <string name="first_onboard_04_body">Run several mesh channels in parallel, including encrypted and open modes, jump between them from one place, and tune how each channel should notify you without leaving the conversation flow.</string>
    <string name="first_onboard_05_title">Groups of people</string>
    <string name="first_onboard_05_body">Split contacts into named groups up to the app limit so routine coordination—friends, work, study squads—stays organized and faster to reach than scrolling one giant list.</string>
    <string name="first_onboard_06_title">Map and coverage</string>
    <string name="first_onboard_06_body">Visualize who is where, blend online tiles with offline map packages when you hike off-grid, and flip between seeing raw node positions versus lightweight beacon-style markers depending on the mission.</string>
    <string name="first_onboard_07_title">Beacons on the mesh</string>
    <string name="first_onboard_07_body">Publish short-lived geographic hints to teammates—think rendezvous pins—with automatic expiry so the map stays readable once the moment has passed.</string>
    <string name="first_onboard_08_title">Radio and system tuning</string>
    <string name="first_onboard_08_body">Adjust LoRa regions and modem behavior, rewrite channel plans, manage security, rename the node and user, wire MQTT or other module integrations when enabled, decide whether GPS is shared with the mesh, and jump into Android system settings when you need deeper OS control.</string>
    <string name="first_onboard_09_title">Everything in chat</string>
    <string name="first_onboard_09_body">Beyond plain text you can send voice notes, attachments, polls, collaborative checklists everyone can update, preset quick phrases, threaded replies, wallpapers, search inside a conversation, and urgent messages in channels and in direct (DM): hold the send button, same as a channel. Where enabled, you can also open an encrypted local archive of past traffic behind its own passphrase.</string>

    <string name="security_regenerate_dialog_body">A new key pair will be generated: a random valid private key; the public key stays empty until the radio derives it. Old keys will no longer match for direct messages with contacts who still trust the previous keys.\n\nIf keys were rotated on more than one device, each radio may keep the other side\'s old public key in NodeDB (trust-on-first-use). Direct messages can stop completely until, on each radio, you remove the peer from the node list / NodeDB or reset NodeDB (Chat → Settings), then wait for fresh NodeInfo.</string>
    <string name="security_dm_tofu_after_key_change">If direct messages stopped: on this radio and on your contact\'s radio, remove each other from NodeDB (Nodes tab) or use NodeDB reset in chat settings. Otherwise the firmware keeps trusting the old public key (known firmware limitation).</string>

    <string name="nodes_forget_node_title">Remove / forget this node?</string>
    <string name="nodes_forget_node_body">The node will be removed only from the app cache (not from the radio NodeDB). It may reappear after new mesh traffic.</string>
    <string name="nodes_forget_node_yes">Yes</string>
    <string name="nodes_forget_node_no">No</string>
    <string name="nodes_forget_need_device">Bind a node to manage the list cache.</string>
    <string name="nodes_forget_node_self_denied">You can\'t remove your own node from the cache.</string>
